    <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Basics</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
      This page helps you decide what to protect, from whom, and what “good enough” looks like. We focus on reducing
      exposure and hardening the accounts attackers most often target.
    </p>

    <section id="threat-model" class="mt-8 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">A quick threat model</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
        You don’t need paranoia; you need clarity. Answer these questions:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
        <li><strong>What are you protecting?</strong> (accounts, finances, physical location, family)</li>
        <li><strong>Who might target you?</strong> (ex-partner, scammer, stalker, random attacker)</li>
        <li><strong>How could they get leverage?</strong> (password reuse, public records, social posts)</li>
        <li><strong>What would “harm” look like?</strong> (account takeover, identity theft, threats, job impact)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="osint" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">OSINT in one paragraph</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
        Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) is information about you that’s publicly available or easily obtained: old
        usernames, photos, relatives, addresses, employer info, school affiliations, court records, and more. The goal is
        to reduce what’s public and make your accounts hard to take over.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="accounts" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Accounts: the big 4 controls</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">1) Unique passwords</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Password reuse turns one leak into many account takeovers. Use a password manager and change the “important”
            accounts first: email, Apple/Google, bank, social.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">2) MFA (2FA)</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Prefer an authenticator app or a security key. SMS is better than nothing, but it’s weaker.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">3) Recovery security</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Attackers often use password resets. Secure your email inbox, set strong recovery options, and remove old phone
            numbers and emails.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">4) Updates</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Keep your phone and laptop updated. Most real-world attacks succeed because devices are unpatched.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="phishing" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Phishing: what to look for (and what to do)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          Most account takeovers start with social engineering: an email, text, phone call, or DM that pressures you into
          clicking a link or sharing a code.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold">Common red flags</p>
            <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
              <li><strong>Urgency</strong>: “act now,” “your account will be closed.”</li>
              <li><strong>Unexpected MFA codes</strong>: you get a code you didn’t request.</li>
              <li><strong>Link mismatches</strong>: the visible link text doesn’t match where it goes.</li>
              <li><strong>Payment pressure</strong>: gift cards, crypto, wire transfers.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold">Safer response</p>
            <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
              <li><strong>Don’t click</strong> the link or open attachments.</li>
              <li><strong>Verify</strong> by navigating to the official site/app yourself.</li>
              <li><strong>Lock down</strong> the account: change password + enable MFA.</li>
              <li><strong>Report</strong> scams using official channels (see Resources).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
